entry.title: language_pack_manager: Init and shut down with `DlcserviceClient`
entry.content:
Before this CL, `DlcserviceClient` is a singleton using

`base::NoDestructor`, which is instantiated in a thread-safe mannger the

first time `GetInstance()` is called.



In tests, `DlcserviceClient` is repeatedly constructed and destructed,

but `LanguagePackManager` remains a singleton. The observer in the

`LanguagePackManager` is not updated after the first test, resulting in

DLC observer test failures if it was not the first test run.



To fix this, there are various solutions:



- Reset the observer to `DlcserviceClient` inside the existing

`ResetForTesting()` method. While this would result in a small change,

we would continue to encounter bugs stemming from the root cause of

"class state was forgotten to be reset in `ResetForTesting()`".



- Replace `base::NoDestructor` with a global heap-allocated instance,

instantiated in `GetInstance` if it does not exist. For tests, there

are two possible alternatives:

- Destroy the global instance during tests using a new

`ShutdownForTesting()` static method, which replaces

`ResetForTesting()`.

- Use a test-local `LanguagePackManager` instance.

Unfortunately, this would make `GetInstance()` not thread safe (unless

a mutex is used).



- Make `LanguagePackManager` owned by a parent class, likely

`ash::Shell`, and instantiate a test-local `LanguagePackManager` in

tests. This would also eliminate all the bugs stemming from forgetting

to reset state, while keeping `GetInstance()` thread safe.

While this is a good idea in theory, this unfortunately causes test

crashes in other tests which instantiate `ash::Shell` - these test

instantiate a `LanguagePackManager` without a global

`DlcserviceClient`, causing `LanguagePackManager` to observe a nullptr

`DlcserviceClient` and crash.



- Replace `base::NoDestructor` with a global heap-allocated instance,

instantiated and shut down in the same code paths that

`DlcserviceClient` is instantiated and shut down. For tests, we have

the same two alternatives as the previous global heap-allocated

instance solution.

This addresses the shortcomings of the previous two solutions, and

aligns us with `DlcserviceClient` to ensure that we should never

instantiate `LanguagePackManager` without a valid global

`DlcserviceClient`.



Out of all the solutions, only the last one does not have any

shortcomings, and so is implemented in this CL.



To ensure that tests are clean, we set the global instance from the

`LanguagePackManager` constructors and destructors, so a test-scoped

`LanguagePackManager` can easily be constructed by having a local

variable in a test. The alternative, having a `ShutdownForTesting()`

static method, would require explicit shutdown logic in tests instead of

using RAII.

compression dictionaries.

This CL also changes HttpBasicStream::GetSSLInfo() and

WebSocketBasicHandshakeStream::GetSSLInfo() not to use

HttpStreamParser::GetSSLInfo() because we want call these methods before

initializing the HttpStreamParser.



HttpNetworkTransaction::DoConnectedCallback() is called before

HttpNetworkTransaction::DoInitStream() initializes the HttpStreamParser.



- HttpNetworkTransaction::DoConnectedCallback()

- HttpNetworkTransaction::DoInitStream()

-> HttpBasicState::Initialize()

-> std::make_unique()

entry.title: Fix run permission context unittests on Windows
entry.content:
If we use the default temp environment variable on Windows, failure

will occur when executing the following unit test:

unit_tests --gtest_filter=ChromeFileSystemAccessPermissionContextTest

.ConfirmSensitiveEntryAccess_DangerousFile



Because before checking the file extension, it will check whether the

directory of the file is blocked. As mentioned in the issue and

comments, the temp path returned by ::GetTempPath depends on the

user's settings, and the default temp path is a sub-path of a blocking

path(base::DIR_LOCAL_APP_DATA), causing false to be returned when

checking whether it is a blocking path



Since home_dir(base::DIR_HOME) is always a non-blocking path, in order

to solve the above problem, we can override the home directory with

ScopedPathOverride (even if the directory is located under the temp

path) in the test code, so that the file extension can be checked

normally



Bug: 1499509

get responses. Removes the temporary CPU-specific entry points in

GraphTestHarness-based unit tests that don't initialize the graph

sequence.

* Rewrites the ScopedCPUQuery shim to use the public API. A followup

will delete the shim and use ScopedResourceUsageQuery directly from

its callers.

entry.title: [IntersectionOptimization] Accumulate scroll delta per IntersectionObservation
entry.content:
UMA metrics added in crrev.com/1193840 show that most

IntersectionObservations have big min_scroll_delta_to_update, but

most LocalFrameViews have very small min_scroll_delta_to_update. This

means that a few IntersectionObservations with small

min_scroll_delta_to_update cause the optimization not effective.



Now track accumulated scroll delta per IntersectionObservation so that

we can still skip update for a IntersectionObservation with a big

min_scroll_delta_to_update despite other IntersectionObservations with

small min_scroll_delta_to_update.



Bug: 1400495

entry.title: Downgrade NOTREACHED in `NGOffsetMapping::GetMappingUnitsForNode`
entry.content:
This patch downgrades `NOTREACHED` in `NGOffsetMapping::

GetMappingUnitsForNode` which sudently jumped in M120.



This happens when `OffsetMapping` data is inconsistent (i.e., mapping

units for a `LayoutText` doesn't match its `TextNode`) and need to look

into each cases[1], but minidumps for this don't provide enough

reproducible cases to look further.



Downgrading a NOTREACHED to DUMP_WILL_BE_NOTREACHED_NORETURN excludes it

from the kNotReachedIsFatal experiment and avoids stability risk during

experiment rollout.



[1] crbug.com/964871#c7

entry.title: Properly scale the folder icon up when dragging
entry.content:
Updates how folder icon view is scaled to be more similar to how app

items are scaled up.



`UpdateIconView()` now updates the folder icon scale, so the folder icon

content gets scaled up when folder item view is scaled up when

initiating drag (without this, the folder content may look pixelated

when scaled up).



Changes the target bounds size for folder when calculating drop bounds

for a dragged folder item.



Scales the size of the folder background by drag icon scale when

creating folder drag image.



While here, remove no longer used ClippedFolderIconImageSource (which

was used for old folder view, which contained a single icon that was

clipped to the expected folder size). And rename unclipped_icon to

folder_icon in AppListConfig (unclipped naming is a leftover from the

old folder icon painting logic).



Changes the folder and extended background a view that paints to layer

instead of a layer owner added to region below the icon view, which

makes managing background bounds easier - views had assumption that the

layers in region below the view had the same bounds as the view itself,

which is no longer the case.

Before, the expandedCategories_ object was using the category's label

as the key to determine if the category was expanded or not. The issue

is that for labels with periods, Polymer interprets the periods as

getting an object's subproperties (eg. 'categories_.U.S.' becomes

'categories_['U']['S']'. Using index is better in every way anyway as

the categories don't change in the lifetime of the UI.
